AstraZeneca, BAE, BT, Rolls-Royce: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   A d r i a   C i m i n o
-- 
2011-07-28T06:29:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-27/afren-diageo-hsbc-rolls-royce-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  September futures on the FTSE 100 Index lost 1.2 percent to
5,755.5 at 7:28 a.m. in London.  The FTSE 100 fell 73.15 points, or 1.2 percent, to 5,856.58
yesterday. The FTSE All-Share Index dropped 1.2 percent and
Ireland’s ISEQ Index retreated 1.3 percent.  Afren Plc (AFR)  : The U.K. oil and gas explorer acquired
interests in two production sharing contracts in the Kurdistan
region of  Iraq  for $588 million. The shares fell 1.9 percent to
146.2 pence.  AstraZeneca Plc (AZN)  : The drugmaker reported second-
quarter sales of $8.43 billion, compared with an average analyst
estimate of $8.23 billion. The stock retreated 1.3 percent to
3,010 pence.  BAE Systems Plc (BA/)  :  Europe ’s largest arms company
reported first-half earnings before interest taxes and
amortization excluding extraordinary items of 968 million pounds
($1.58 billion) compared with an analyst estimate of 843.5
million pounds. The shares fell 2.9 percent to 292.5 pence.  BP Plc (BP/)  : Employees shouldn’t be allowed to sue the
company’s retirement savings plan managers for investing too
heavily in BP stock because the workers chose to invest in those
shares, company lawyers said. The stock declined 0.7 percent to
460.20 pence.  BT Group Plc (BT/A)  (BT/A LN): Britain’s biggest phone company
said first-quarter sales declined 5 percent to 4.76 billion
pounds, matching analyst estimates. The shares fell 2.5 percent
to 190.7 pence.  Diageo Plc (DGE)  : The maker of Johnnie Walker scotch and
Smirnoff vodka will pay more than $16 million to resolve U.S.
regulatory claims the firm bribed officials in  South Korea ,
 India  and Thailand to win sales and tax benefits. The shares
fell 1.2 percent to 1,261 pence.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  : The London-based lender is
close to a decision to cut thousands of jobs, Sky News reported,
citing people familiar with the matter. The stock fell 1.6
percent to 601.9 pence.  Mondi Plc (MNDI)  : Europe’s largest maker of office paper
said first-half operating profit from continuing operations
increased 74 percent to 354 million euros. The stock gained 0.6
percent to 627.5 pence.  Reed Elsevier Plc (REL)  : The owner of the LexisNexis
database and New Scientist magazine reported first-half revenue
of 2.9 billion pounds. The shares fell 0.9 percent to 559.5
pence.  Rolls-Royce Holdings Plc (RR/ LN): The world’s second-
largest maker of  jet engines  said underlying first-half pretax
profit rose 28 percent to 595 million pounds. The stock declined
1.2 percent to 641.5 pence.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  : Europe’s largest oil
company reported net income of $8.66 billion in the second
quarter of the year. That compared with profit of $4.39 billion
in the year-earlier period. The stock dropped 1.5 percent to
2,265 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
